1. Introduction

In this document a data set is analyzed, a relevant research question is created and some exploratory data analysis is performed. Then a linear regression model is developed and this model is used to do some prediction.

2. Setup

2.1. Load Packages

The “dplyr” package will be used to manipulate data. The “ggplot2”, “gridExtra” and “GGally” packages will be used to visualize data.

# Loading the necessary R packages
library(statsr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)
library(GGally)

2.2. Load Data

# Loading the data set
load("movies.Rdata")

3. Data

The data set is a data frame containing 651 observations and 32 variables. The observations consist in randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. The variables are described in detail in the next section.

Since the samples have been randomly selected, it is possible to generalize the results to the entire population of the movies released before 2016. Based on the listed studios, it might be safer to limit the population to US movies.

Note that, due to the observational nature of the survey, it is only possible to find associations between different variables but it is not possible to deduce any causal relationship.

A potential cause for bias is due to the fact that not all people might decide to vote for the movie.

4. Research Question

The aim of this study is to find out what are the attributes that make a movie popular.

Movies’ popularity will be measured by using the variables audience_score and imdb_rating.

The following variables might have influence to movies’ popularity:

  • title_type
  • genre
  • runtime
  • critics_rating
  • critics_score
  • best_pic_nom
  • best_pic_win
  • best_actor_win
  • best_actress_win
  • best_dir_win

It is assumed that attributes such as the title of the movie, the studio that produced the movie, the MPAA classification or the time when the movie was released do not affect the popularity of the movie.

Which of the above listed attributes are associated to the popularity of a movie?

This information would be very useful for studios since it would give some guidance about, for example, what genre is more popular or whether the runtime affects considerably the popularity of the movie.

5. Exploratory Data Analysis

5.1. Data Cleaning

There are NA values in the column runtime.

# Extracting observations with no NA values from the column "runtime"
nrow(movies[complete.cases(movies[ , 4]),])
## [1] 650

The number of observations with no NA values in the column “runtime” is 650. Therefore, by creating a new data frame which does not contain NA values for the variables of interest, only 1 out of 651 observations is lost.

# Creating a clean dataframe
movies.clean <- movies[complete.cases(movies[ , 4]),]

5.2. Data Preparation

The following variables are coded as factor with two levels, having logical meaning of “no” and “yes” as follows: “no” = 1, “yes” = 2. The variables will be converted into logical variables.

  • best_pic_nom
  • best_pic_win
  • best_actor_win
  • best_actress_win
  • best_dir_win

The code below shows the first variable. The code used for checking for the other variables has been omitted for brevity.

# Showing the summary for the variable "best_pic_nom"
movies.clean %>%
  group_by(best_pic_nom) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   best_pic_nom count
##   <fct>        <int>
## 1 no             628
## 2 yes             22

The variable is converted into numerical.

# Converting the variable "best_pic_nom" into integer and storing the result in the new dataframe "movies.mod"
movies.mod <- movies.clean %>%
  mutate(best_pic_nom = as.integer(best_pic_nom))
# Showing again the summary for the variable "best_pic_nom"
movies.mod %>%
  group_by(best_pic_nom) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   best_pic_nom count
##          <int> <int>
## 1            1   628
## 2            2    22

The wished coding for the variable is the following: “no” = 0, “yes” = 1. The wished change is performed below and the result is verified.

# Changing the coding of the variable "best_pic_nom"
movies.mod <- movies.mod %>%
  mutate(best_pic_nom = ifelse(best_pic_nom == 1, 0, 1))
movies.mod %>%
  group_by(best_pic_nom) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   best_pic_nom count
##          <dbl> <int>
## 1           0.   628
## 2           1.    22

Finally, the variable is converted into logical.

# Converting the variable "best_pic_nom" into logical
movies.mod <- movies.mod %>%
  mutate(best_pic_nom = as.logical(best_pic_nom))
movies.mod %>%
  group_by(best_pic_nom) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   best_pic_nom count
##   <lgl>        <int>
## 1 FALSE          628
## 2 TRUE            22

The same process is applied to all the other variables listed above.

# Converting into integer, changing the coding, converting into logical
movies.mod <- movies.mod %>%
  mutate(best_pic_win = as.integer(best_pic_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_pic_win = ifelse(best_pic_win == 1, 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(best_pic_win = as.logical(best_pic_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_actor_win = as.integer(best_actor_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_actor_win = ifelse(best_actor_win == 1, 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(best_actor_win = as.logical(best_actor_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_actress_win = as.integer(best_actress_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_actress_win = ifelse(best_actress_win == 1, 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(best_actress_win = as.logical(best_actress_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_dir_win = as.integer(best_dir_win)) %>%
  mutate(best_dir_win = ifelse(best_dir_win == 1, 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(best_dir_win = as.logical(best_dir_win))

A new variable which combines the variables best_actor_win and best_actress_win is created.

The new variable best_act_wintells whether or not one of the main actor and/or actress in the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes). Note that this is not necessarily whether the actor/actress won an Oscar for his/her role in the given movie.

# Adding the new variable "best_act_win"
movies.mod <- movies.mod %>%
  mutate(best_act_win = best_actor_win | best_actress_win)

One more variable is added to contain the row number of the dataframe: row_number.

# Adding a variable for the row number
movies.mod <- movies.mod %>%
  mutate(row_number = c(1:nrow(movies.mod)))

5.2.1. Summary of Modification to Data

The following process has been applied to the variables listed below: a conversion from factor to integer, a code conversion to “no” = 0 and “yes” = 1, a conversion to logical variable.

  • best_pic_nom
  • best_pic_win
  • best_actor_win
  • best_actress_win
  • best_dir_win

The new variable best_act_win has been introduced as Boolean sum of best_actor_win and best_actress_win.

The new variable row_number which contains the row number of the data frame has been introduced.

5.3. Data Analysis

In this section it will be investigated how the variables audience_score and imdb_rating are related to the other variables. Also, potential dependencies between explanatory variables will be investigated.

5.3.1. Numerical Variables

The first step is to check how the variable audience_score is related to other numerical variables.

  • imdb_rating
  • runtime
  • critics_score
# Creating a new dataframe containing only the relevant variables
movies.num <- movies.mod %>%
  select(audience_score, imdb_rating, runtime, critics_score)
# Checking correlation of the numerical variables
ggpairs(movies.num)

It appears that there is good correlation between the two variables that measure movie popularity among consumers: imdb_rating and audience_score (0.865). Therefore, only one of them will be used to measure movies’ polularity: audience_score.

There is also good correlation between audience_score and critics_score (0.704), whereas there is no good correlation between audience_score and runtime.

5.3.2. Categorical Variables

  • title_type
  • genre
  • critics_rating
# Box Plots of Audience Score for different values of Title Type

There is strong variability of audience_score with genre. The median rating for “Documentaries” is the highest at 86 while for “Horror” is only 43 (half of the previous value). As expected, movies that have been nominated for a best picture Oscar have higher audience scores. There is little variability in the audience score within the movies that have received the nomination. There are only 22 of such movies.

A similar result is obtained by looking at the movies who won a best picture Oscar versus the others. Note that the sample size of the Oscar winning movies is only 7.

The audience score does not seem related to whether the main actor/actress has won a Oscar in the past.

The average audience score for movies where the director has won a Oscar in the past is slightly higher but the difference does not seem to be big.

5.3.4. Dependent Explanatory Variables

There is reason to believe that the following couples of variables might be dependent:

  • audience_rating, audience_score
  • critics_rating, critics_score
  • best_pic_nom, best_pic_win

audience_rating, audience_score

# Creating a Box Plot of Audience Score for different values of Audience Rating
ggplot(data = movies.mod, aes(x = audience_rating, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_boxplot () + xlab("Audience Rating") + ylab("Audience Score") + ggtitle("Audience Score vs. Audience Rating") + 
     theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Table of Audience Score vs. Audience Rating
movies.mod %>%
  group_by(audience_rating) %>%
  summarise(count = n(), audience_score_mean = mean(audience_score))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   audience_rating count audience_score_mean
##   <fct>           <int>               <dbl>
## 1 Spilled           275                41.9
## 2 Upright           375                77.3

The variable audience_rating is by definition dependent on the variable audience_score. The above plot and table show that there is a big difference in the mean of audience_score for different values of audience_rating.

Inferential statistics is needed to find out if those differences are statistically significant.

  • mu_aud_score_spilled is the mean of the audience score for those observations where audience rating has the value “spilled”
  • mu_aud_score_upright is the mean of the audience score for those observations where audience rating has the value “upright”"

The following hypothesis test is performed:

H0: mu_aud_score_spilled = mu_aud_score_upright
HA: mu_aud_score_spilled ≠ mu_aud_score_upright

# Hypothesis test for audience_score 
inference(y = audience_score, x = audience_rating, data = movies.mod, statistic = "mean", type = "ht", null = 0, alternative = "twosided", method = "theoretical", sig_level = 0.05)
## Response variable: numerical
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_Spilled = 275, y_bar_Spilled = 41.9345, s_Spilled = 11.217
## n_Upright = 375, y_bar_Upright = 77.3173, s_Upright = 9.3402
## H0: mu_Spilled =  mu_Upright
## HA: mu_Spilled != mu_Upright
## t = -42.5908, df = 274
## p_value = < 0.0001

The two distributions are not perfectly normal but the sample sizes are high enough to relax a bit this condition. Therefore, the method used above is applicable. The p-value has a very small value (0.0001) which is smaller than the significance level (0,05). Therefore, the null hypothesis H0 is rejected and this means that the difference in the two means is statistically significant.

For the inferential statistics, ANOVA is used. The box plot above indicates some skew (which would be confirmed by a histogram) but the sample sizes are big enough not to cause worries. The box plot also shows some variability across the groups, which might be a slighter bigger concern for applying ANOVA but the difference in variability does not seem to be huge.

# Performing ANOVA
anova.result = aov(critics_score ~ critics_rating, data=movies.mod)
summary(anova.result)
##                 Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## critics_rating   2 406026  203013    1115 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals      647 117849     182                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Since the p-value is very small (2e-16) and definitely smaller than 0.05, the analysis provides convincing evidence that at least one pair of population means are different from each other.

##   <lgl>        <int>        <int>
## 1 FALSE          628            1
## 2 TRUE            22            6

Not surprisingly, the EDA shows very big percentage of Oscar winners among those movies who have been nominated for best picture.

The inferential statistics below confirms that the success in winning a Best Picture Oscar is associated to a Best Picture Oscar Nomination. The following hypothesis test has been done:

H0: p_best_pic_win_nom_true = p_best_pic_win_nom_false
HA: p_best_pic_win_nom_true ≠ p_best_pic_win_nom_false

where:

  • p_best_pic_win_nom_true is the proportion of movies that won the best picture Oscar among those who have been nominated for best picture
  • p_best_pic_win_nom_false is the proportion of movies that won the best picture Oscar among those who have not been nominated for best picture
# Hypothesis test for best_pic_win 
inference(y = best_pic_win, x = best_pic_nom, data = movies.mod, statistic = "proportion", type = "ht", success = "TRUE", null = 0, alternative = "twosided", method = "theoretical", sig_level = 0.05)
## Response variable: categorical (2 levels, success: TRUE)
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_FALSE = 628, p_hat_FALSE = 0.0016
## n_TRUE = 22, p_hat_TRUE = 0.2727
## H0: p_FALSE =  p_TRUE
## HA: p_FALSE != p_TRUE
## z = -12.111
## p_value = < 0.0001

5.4. Conclusion

There seem to be an association between audience_score and the following variables:

  • critics_score
  • genre
  • best_pic_nom
  • best_pic_win

Without performing any inferential statistics, it is not possible to be certain that such associations are statistically significant.

The variable best_pic_win depends from the variable best_pic_nom.

6. Modeling

6.1. Model Selection Method

The stepwise backward selection method will be used to find a linear regression model. By starting with the full model, variables will be dropped till a parsimonious model is reached.

In order to find the most statistically significant predictors, the p-value method is preferred over the adjusted R2 method.

6.2. Selected Variables

The variables inserted in the full model are the following ones:

  • audience_score
  • title_type
  • genre
  • runtime
  • critics_score
  • best_pic_nom
  • best_act_win
  • best_dir_win

It is assumed that attributes such as the title of the movie, the studio that produced the movie, the MPAA classification or the time when the movie was released do not affect the popularity of the movie.

Using imdb_rating would be an alternative way to monitor movies’ popularity. It has been decided to use audience_score instead.

Due to concerns of possible collinearity, the variable critics_rating has not been included in the model, due to the inclusion of the variable critics_score.

For a similar reason, only one of the two variables best_pic_nom and best_pic_win has been included.

6.3. Model Selection

The p-value for the all model is 2.2e-16, which is lower than the significance level of 0.05. This means that at least one of the predictor is a significant one.

The variable which has the highest p-value is best_dir_win, with a value of 0,91063 that is much higher than 0.05. This means that whether or not the director of the movie ever won an Oscar is not a significant predictor of the audience score, given all the other variables are included in the model.

This result is consistent to what found in the Exploratory Data Analysis section.

Therefore, the variable best_dir_win is omitted and the model is refit.

6.4. Model Interpretation

The final parsimonious model (model.iteration4) is shown above. It has 3 predictors: genre, critics_score and best_pic_nom. The response variable is audience_score.

The adjusted R squared of the model is 0.5267. This means that 52.67% of the variability in the audience score is explained by this model.

All else hold constant, for every one unit increase in critics score, the model predicts a 0.44422 increase in audience score on average.

All else hold constant, if the movie was nominated for a best picture Oscar the audience score is predicted to increase by 10.04271 on average.

All else hold constant, the genre of the movie is predicted to have bigger or smaller effect depending on the actual genre. A “Documentary” is predicted to have a positive effect on the audience score of 9.16840 on average compared to the reference level of “Action & Adventure”. On the other hand, a “Horror” movie is predicted to decrease the audience score of 9.08053 on average compared to the reference level.

6.5. Model Diagnostic

In this section it will be assessed if the linear model defined above is reliable. Therefore, the model will be checked against the following conditions:

  • Linear relationship between the numerical explanatory variables and the response variable
  • Near normal residuals
  • Constant variability of the residuals
  • Independence of the residuals

6.5.1. Linear Relationship between x and y

The following picture is a scatter plot of the residuals versus the variable critics_score which allows for considering also the other two explanatory variables, compared to a scatterplot of audience_rating versus critics_score.

# Plotting the Residuals vs. the Numerical Explanatory Variable
ggplot(data = model.iteration4, aes(x = movies.mod$critics_score, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  xlab("Critics Scores") +
  ylab("Residuals") + ggtitle("Residuals vs. the Numerical Explanatory Variable") + 
     theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

The wished result would be a random scatter around zero. The diagram shows more closeness to the zero in the right part, especially in the upper one. This means that the model is slightly more accurate for high values of the critics score. However, the deviance from the ideal random scatter is not huge.

6.5.2. Near Normal Residuals

The following histogram of the residuals shows an almost normal distribution.

# Histogram of the residuals
ggplot(data = model.iteration4, aes(x = .resid)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 3) +
  xlab("Residuals") + ggtitle("Histogram of the Residuals") + 
     theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

6.5.3. Constant Variability of the Residuals

The scatterplot of the residuals versus the predicted values confirms the result of the first diagram: a slight tendency towards a fan shaped plot, which shows that the model is not ideal. However, by plotting the absolute value of the residuals versus the predicted values this trend is no longer visible.

6.5.4. Independence of the Residuals

There is no reason to suspect dependence of the observation and a time series structure. The following diagram provides the confirmation.

# Plotting the Residuals vs. the order of data collection
ggplot(data = model.iteration4, aes(x = movies.mod$row_number, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  xlab("Order of Data Collection") +
  ylab("Residuals") + ggtitle("Residuals vs. the Order of Data Collection") + 
     theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

6.5.5. Conclusions

The conditions required for the multiple linear regression model to be valid are satisfied.

7. Prediction

The model is tested by doing some prediction related to movies that have not been included in the original data set.

The movie “Captain Fantastic” is not contained in the original dataset.

# Searching for the movie "Captain Fantastic"
result <- movies %>%
  filter(title == "Captain Fantastic")
nrow(result)
## [1] 0

The audience score at the time of writing this study is: 85% (’)

The movie is classified as a “Comedy/Drama”. (’’)

The critics score is 83% (’).

The movie has received many awards, including Best Performance by an Actor in a Leading Role Oscar nominee and NTFCA Best Picture nominee but has not been receiving an Oscar nominee for Best Picture (‘’’).

(’) https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/captain_fantastic

(’’) http://www.imdb.com/search/title?year=2016,2016&title_type=feature&sort=moviemeter,asc&page=1&ref_=adv_prv

(‘’’) http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3553976/awards

Since this movie might belong to 2 different genres, two new dataframes are created to contain the data of this movie.

# "Captain Fantastic" movie data (genre = Drama)
cap_fant_d <- data.frame(genre = "Drama", critics_score = 83, best_pic_nom = FALSE)
# "Captain Fantastic" movie data (genre = Comedy)
cap_fant_c <- data.frame(genre = "Comedy", critics_score = 83, best_pic_nom = FALSE)

The prediction is done below, including a 95% confidence interval which provides a measure of uncertainty around the prediction.

# Making the prediction (genre = Drama)
predict(model.iteration4, cap_fant_d, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##       fit      lwr    upr
## 1 74.0189 46.61778 101.42

The result of the prediction is an audience score of 74.

Also, with 95% confidence, a Drama movie which gets a critic score of 83 and has not received an Oscar nomination for best picture is expected to have an audience score between 46.62 and 101.42 (actually 100 since that is the maximum value).

# Making the prediction (genre = Comedy)
predict(model.iteration4, cap_fant_c, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 71.08346 43.52904 98.63788

The result of the prediction is an audience score of 71.

With 95% confidence, a Comedy movie which gets a critic score of 83 and has not received an Oscar nomination for best picture is expected to have an audience score between 43.53 and 98.64.

The model has underestimated in both cases and shows quite a bit of variability. It does not surprise that the first prediction shows a result closer to the measured value since the movie genre is closer to “Drama” than to “Comedy”.

Since the movie received so many nominations, it is interesting to check the result of the prediction by setting the variable best_pic_nom = TRUE. The result of such prediction could give some hint about how to improve the model.

# "Captain Fantastic" movie data ("best_pic_nom" = TRUE)
cap_fant <- data.frame(genre = "Drama", critics_score = 83, best_pic_nom = TRUE)
# Making the prediction
predict(model.iteration4, cap_fant, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit     lwr     upr
## 1 84.06161 56.0972 112.026

This time the result (84) is pretty close to the measured value (85).

8. Conclusion

This study has showed that a possible model to predict the audience score of a new movie on Rotten Tomatoes is to use a multiple linear regression model which contains 3 explanatory variables:

  • The genre of the movie (categorical variable)
  • Critics score on Rotten Tomatoes (numerical variable)
  • Whether or not the movie has received an Oscar nomination for best picture (logical variable)

Variables such as movies’ runtime seem not to have a significant effect on the audience score.

52.67% of the variability in the audience score is expected to be predicted with this model.

The high variability of the model has been confirmed by testing it with one new movie. The result of such test suggests that Oscar nomination for best picture alone might be not sufficient for an accurate model.

In future research it might be useful to collect data about other types of awards and summarize them in new variables to be added to the data set. It would be interesting to check if including some of those new variables in the models as predictors increases model’s accuracy.
